</div></div>

<!-- ░░ OVERVIEW MODE (plain language) ░░ -->
<div class="ov-only">
<section class="dsec ov-intro"><div class="wrap">
  <div class="sec-head"><div><div class="eyebrow">In layman’s terms</div><h2>Equities, in plain words.</h2></div><span class="fresh-tag">data through {dataThrough}</span></div>
  <div class="kpibar ov-kpi">
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-k">Market mood</div><div class="kpi-v sm">Narrow &amp; cautious</div><div class="kpi-meta"><span class="vt">read</span></div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-k">How broad is the rally</div><div class="kpi-v">{breadthPct}</div><div class="kpi-meta"><span class="vt">above 50-day</span></div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-k">Are stocks pricey?</div><div class="kpi-v sm">Yes — above norm</div><div class="kpi-meta"><span class="vt">baseline</span></div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-k">Reward for owning stocks</div><div class="kpi-v sm">Thin (≈3.2%)</div><div class="kpi-meta"><span class="vt">baseline</span></div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="ov-beats">
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">What equities are doing</div><p>The headline US index keeps hitting new highs — but <b>most individual stocks aren’t joining in</b>. A small group of giant, AI-linked companies is doing nearly all the lifting; only about <b>{breadthPct}</b> of stocks sit above their recent trend.</p></div>
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">Why it matters</div><p>A market that rises on fewer and fewer names is <b>more fragile</b> — if the leaders stumble, there’s less underneath to cushion a fall. And because stocks are already expensive, the extra reward for owning them instead of safe bonds (the <span class="gloss" data-def={G['ERP']}>equity risk premium</span>) is unusually thin.</p></div>
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">Who’s exposed — winners &amp; losers</div><p><b>It depends on what happens next.</b> If the Iran–Gulf conflict worsens, {ovWinTxt} tend to benefit, while {ovLoseTxt} tend to suffer — and those roles <b>flip</b> if there’s a ceasefire. “Winner” and “loser” here mean <i>relative to before the event, in the scenario that actually plays out</i>, not a forecast or a recommendation.</p><a class="ov-link" href="/markets/equities#catalysts">See the full winners &amp; losers table →</a></div>
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">What’s driving it now</div><p>Four lasting forces and one live event. The lasting forces: the <b>AI investment boom</b> (lifting the giants), <b>interest rates</b> (which weigh on pricey growth stocks), <b>company earnings</b>, and <b>how crowded</b> popular trades have become. On top sits the live event — the <b>Iran–Gulf conflict</b>, which reprices energy and the Gulf markets. No single force explains the move; we name them all, including what we can’t explain.</p></div>
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">What to watch</div><p>Signs the picture is changing: <b>more stocks</b> joining the rally, the reward-for-risk improving, company forecasts turning <b>down</b>, or the conflict escalating toward the Strait of Hormuz. On the calendar: <b>Fed meetings, inflation and jobs reports, earnings season, and OPEC oil decisions</b>.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="ov-foot">
    <span class="dconf medium">Overall confidence: medium</span>
    <a class="cta-frame cta-h" href="/markets/equities">Open the Analyst view — full data, tables &amp; sources →</a>
  </div>
  <p class="tnote">Hover any <span class="gloss" data-def="A specialist term, explained in plain language when you hover.">underlined term</span> for a plain definition. This is research and analysis, not investment advice.</p>
</div></section>
</div>

<!-- ░░ ANALYST DESK (full framework) ░░ -->
<div class="an-only">
<!-- competing drivers -->
